-- Australia, N.Z. Stocks: Bendigo, BHP Billiton, Duet, Orica, Pike, Santos
-- Shani Raja
-- 2010-07-23T06:50:33Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-23/australia-n-z-stocks-bendigo-bhp-billiton-duet-orica-pike-santos.html

          
          
             Australia’s  S&P/ASX 200 Index  gained
1.9 percent, the most since July 8, to 4,458.40 at the close of
trading in Sydney. The Australian gauge gained 0.8 percent this
week. New Zealand’s  NZX 50 Index  advanced 0.5 percent to
2,994.90 in Wellington, taking its climb in the last five days
to 0.3 percent.  
 The following were among the most active shares in the
market today. Stock symbols are in parentheses after company
names.  
 Mining shares: Copper futures rose 2.3 percent yesterday in
New York, the fourth straight day of gains.  BHP Billiton  (BHP
AU), the world’s largest mining company, advanced 2.1 percent to
A$39.68.  Rio Tinto Group  (RIO AU), the third largest, increased
2.4 percent to A$69.86.  
 Oil companies: Crude oil in New York rose 3.6 percent to
$79.30 a barrel yesterday, the highest settlement since May 5.  
 Woodside Petroleum Ltd.  (WPL AU), Australia’s second-
largest oil and gas producer, advanced 2.2 percent to A$41.92.
Separately, Woodside said sales rose 48 percent in the second
quarter.  
 Rival  Santos Ltd.  (STO AU) climbed 2.1 percent to A$13.84.
Santos had its rating raised to “overweight” from “equal-
weight” by analysts at Morgan Stanley.  
 Bendigo and Adelaide Bank Ltd.  (BEN AU) gained 2.5 percent
to A$8.21. The regional lender had its rating raised to “equal-
weight” from “underweight” by analysts at Morgan Stanley.  
 Orica Ltd.  (ORI AU) rallied 1.7 percent to A$25.42. The
world’s largest industrial explosives maker plans to start
building a $500 million petrochemical plant in Peru next year,
Chairman  Graeme Liebelt  told reporters in Lima after meeting
with President  Alan Garcia .  
 New Zealand:  
      Pike River Coal Ltd.  (PRC NZ), which operates a mine on New
Zealand’s South Island, rose 2.2 percent to 95 New Zealand cents.
The stock was raised to “outperform” from “neutral” at
Macquarie Research.  
